Passengers can already do it during the main part of the flight, but many are irritated that they do not have access to their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian carriers consider this decision, which required American airlines to carry out a huge amount of work to meet the new requirements, but pointed out that they do not plan to change their procedures in the near future.
In the Civil Aviation Safety Department, they also noted that they are considering this statement, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical phases of the flight are still in Australia.
The Civil Aviation Flight Safety Authority currently has no special rules governing the use of electronic devices in aircraft, "It said.
This issue is regulated by the rules that require air carriers to ensure safety at any time, and from passengers to comply with the safety rules, which they are informed by the crew members.
Virgin, which has already discussed with the Civil Aviation Safety Authority, the expansion of use on board its entertainment system with Wi-Fi, was not against the changes, but stated that it will follow the instructions of the regulator.
"We would welcome consideration by the Civil Aviation Flight Safety Authority on the issue of permitting the use of electronic devices, because we really think it will improve the quality of customer service now when it (on-board wireless entertainment system) is on our aircraft," said the spokesman.
Qantas said she would adhere to the current rules.
Our current policy is that electronic devices cannot be used during take-off and landing, and in the near future we do not plan to change it," she said.
The decision of the FAU applies to American airlines.
However, we are always interested in regulatory changes that could benefit passengers, and we will certainly carefully study the decision of the FAU and the reasons that caused it.
For U.S. carriers, the impact of the resolution will vary from airline to airline and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will have to prove that their aircraft are resistant to radio interfering from mobile devices, as well as to review manuals, training materials, manual rules and instructions for passengers.
"After the airline will check and confirm the interference resistance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, light electronic devices such as tablets, e-books and smartphones, at any height, said FAU.
In rare cases, poor visibility, the crew will give instructions to passengers to turn off their devices during landing.
