Scientists have shed light on how the movements of the dog's tail are connected with her mood.
Early studies have shown that satisfied dogs are forks tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog), while alarmed dogs wave their tail predominantly in the left.
But now scientists say that other members of the dog family can notice these subtle differences in the tail of the veer and react to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist from the University of Trent, says: "It is well known that people have left and right sides of the brain differently involved in the formation of pathogens that cause positive or negative emotions.
Here we tried to look at it in other species.
He added that just like a person, dogs have the right part of the brain controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotion.
To learn more about how dogs react to versatile tails of other dogs, researchers watched animals when they watched films about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analyzed their behavior.
Probably soon we will understand why their tails sometimes go one way, and sometimes to another
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed dogs videos with dogs - either naturalistic versions, or silhouette to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the tail movement and direct the tail more to the left or to the right.
When the animals saw that otherwise the dog's expressing dog moved the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog's wagging tail), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was mostly inclined to the left (again from the point of view of the dog's wagging tail), their heartbeat was increasing and they looked alarmed.
Professor Valortigara said he did not think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other with the help of these movements.
In fact, he believes that the dogs learned from their experience, what movements they should worry about, and what movements they should not.
He remarks: "If there are several meetings with other dogs and often the wagging of their tail in one direction is connected with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, the dog reacts on the basis of this experience.
Researchers say that these results can give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of the emotions of their animal.
Dog Behavior John Bradshaw, an invited researcher at the University of Bristol University veterinary school, said that this was not the first study to check whether the left and right-handed dogs were important.
Last year, a group of scientists from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left, if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right, if they look at a satisfied dog.
And in another scientific work of the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: " Dogs more often approached the dog-robot, when the wagging of her tail was sent to the left, and not to the right, instead of becoming alarmed, - the opposite behavior in relation to the Italian study.
He said that the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or dog robots as dogs.
It would be useful to study how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
"Wait with different mammals, there is enough evidence that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details are yet to be refined, and the dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be registered, we will probably soon understand why their tails are sometimes directed to one side, and sometimes to another.
