Russia outside the fight for the pollution of cities by cars
Attempts to solve transport problems of major cities were observed in most megacities of the world since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was either about their reconstruction and expansion of highways, or attempts to reduce the demand for road travel, the number of cars and their use time.
The example of Singapore is widely known, where the strict quota of growth of the number of private cars is introduced, and the right to purchase them is bought at auctions.
Its price can double or three times the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, introduced a fee for entry to the city center.
In Germany, for example, in Hamburg and Stuttgart, introduce so-called green areas, where only cars with a certain ecoclass, using high-quality fuel (including biofuel or electric vehicles) are allowed to enter.
The Beijing Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved in 2012 a "five-year plan of clean air" worth about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
As the director of the Department for Transport Pollution Control of the Municipal Environmental Protection Office of Beijing Li Kunchen, the main goal of the five-year plan is to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, the growth of the number of private cars to the level not exceeding 6 million (now 5.2 million), as well as an increase of no more than 5% of the use of fuel per vehicle.
According to the agency, now vehicles in Beijing are responsible for 22.5% of total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program - restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, urban measures of the "green five-year" include an accelerated transition to the European standards of fuel, the introduction of a local system of eco-standards and marking cars and fuel, restricting the entry of cars to the central part of the city, a ban on the use of outdated vehicles (except for the creation of incentive financial programs for the replacement of old cars on hybrid or electric vehicles), the development of electric vehicles (including public and official transport).
Among the automotive innovations of Beijing also includes a ban for all private cars on movement within the fifth transport ring (only in the capital of China there are six) one day per week (corresponding information is contained in the vehicle license plate), as well as the issuance of registration signs for cars based on the lottery (for example, in 2011, the first year of the lottery, the total number of permits for registration of private cars in Beijing was only a third of the number of 2010).
According to the current state program "Environmental protection for 2012-2020," the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Nature, in 2011 "movable sources" accounted for 41% of all emissions of polluting substances into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
In Russia, so far, they are just beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
Mikhail Blinkin, director of the Institute of Transport and Transport Policy of the Higher School of Economics, believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for automobile travel are obviously unpopular, they can be accepted by society only if they are full of universality.
In the case of Moscow, there is a unique problem related to the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters of weakly sensitive to any regulatory impacts - service and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, the total number of which is not less than 200 thousand (about 5% of the total number of the car park in Moscow).
Recently, urbanists from the center of ECOM in St. Petersburg prepared a study, which analyzes the balance of urban areas between residential development, road surface area and the number of vehicles.
The main conclusions of researchers: the city center is provided with roads twice as much as required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in parking or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking, but storage cars, not to expand, but to reduce the roadway (so that the streets become more friendly for pedestrians), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal transport within the territory of the protected area of the historical center (the total territory of about 3212 hectares covering a number of central areas of the city).
The increase in fuel will lead to the tax maneuver, which provides for an increase in the mineral extraction tax on oil simultaneously with the reduction of export duties and increase in excise taxes.
