Drive through mud, rivers and jungle to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Brwelle provides free medical assistance in the countryside in Cameroon
Brwelle and his team spend almost every weekend, taking hundreds of patients
In this West-African country doctors are not so many - only one for 5,000 people
Vote here or through your mobile device
Dr. Georges Brwelle is one of the 10 main characters of CNN in 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to become the Hero of the Year CNN.
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his father return to life and retreat into an unconscious state, wandering around hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamph Bwelle was injured in a car crash in 1981 near Jaunda, the capital of Cameroon.
At first he had only a broken hand, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused the hematum, which reminded itself for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Brwelle.
If we had the money, we would have taken it out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwell accompanied his father for years in crowded clinics and hospitals, receiving any treatment they could receive.
"It's not easy," said Bwell.
You can leave the house at 5 am, run to the hospital to be the first, but you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because they have to wait.
The situation has not changed much since Bwell's father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, in Cameroon only one doctor for 5,000 people.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor for 413 people.
And even if the Cameroons could go to the doctor, many of them would not be able to afford.
Two out of five people in this country live beyond poverty, and almost three-quarters of healthcare expenses in it are private.
The only problem is poverty," said Bwell.
And because of poverty they cannot enjoy their lives.
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwell was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Brwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free operations.
He himself became a doctor and works as a vascular surgeon in the Central Hospital of Jaunda.
He also founded a non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped almost 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday he and up to 30 people are poured into vans, tied to the roofs of medical supplies and travel through rough terrain to visit the village in need of help.
Not always they are accompanied by luck.
Many times they had to push cars through the rivers and dirt.
But when they come, they are met as real heroes: it is a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms that the locals can offer.
Free medical care in these villages is really a holiday occasion, and Bwell with its wide smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join the fun.
The next morning, the brigade begins to take hundreds of patients.
"We welcome 500 people on each trip," said Bwell.
They come from all over the county within a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these clinics weekend provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment from malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - documents necessary for a school that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the brigade conducts simple operations under local anesthesia.
Surgery is usually carried out in the school building, municipality or house; after the procedure, patients get into the postoperative zone to make room for the next person.
Using a generator for the lighting of operating and sanitary treatment of equipment, Bwelle and its volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
This is a low pace, but the purposefulness of the brigade usually helps to support the village musicians.
"They're beating the drums all night, so that we're awake and continue to work," said Bwell.
On Sunday, the brigade members go back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, consisting of Cameroon doctors and foreign medical students, conducted 700 free operations last year, and they know that their help can be of great importance for those to whom they help.
One person explained that the free surgery he received for hernia treatment will allow him to work again.
"This will change the future for me and my family," said the man.
In addition to these clinical receptions on the weekend and work in the hospital, the surgeon Bwell also works at nights in private medical clinics around Jaunde.
It is this second work, he said, that provides 60 % of funding of its non-profit organization; the rest of the funds are covered by private donations.
"I don't even know when he's sleeping," said Katie O'Malley, second-year medical student at the University of Philadelphia, a volunteer in the Bwell group.
He is always in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization, so that you can continue these campaigns.
For future doctors and nurses, such as O'Malley coming from the United States and Europe to join Bwell in fulfilling his tasks, it is an opportunity of practice that they would never have received at home.
"We were able to assist in operations where we helped to remove blood stains or keep the tools for Dr. Bwell, said O'Malley.
As a second-year student, you would never get such an opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medicines.
But upon arrival in Jaund their food, transport and training pays Bwell.
"He's a hero, no doubt, " said O'Malley.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon indefinitely.
For Bwell, almost constant workload is not a difficult test.
To help live a happy life to others, to fulfill the promise given to your father is what brings him great joy.
"I am so happy when I do this work," said Bwell.
And I think of my father.
Hopefully he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to ASCOVIME and see what you can help.
