Goldman Sachs warned about risks for the Russian economy
Goldman Sachs warned of growing risks for the main driver of fragile economic growth in Russia - consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payment on unsecured consumer loans and massive reductions of employees.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed down, but rather the structure of this growth.
Recently, it is completely due to consumption, which almost does not reduce turnover," said Chief Economist of Goldman Sachs in Russia Clemens Graf, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Now the nominal wage growth in Russia is about 10%.
With inflation of 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at approximately the current level, it is expected in Goldman Sachs.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so they are likely to optimize the costs of personnel.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, the GDP is only 2%, - said Mr. Graf.
The companies faced a reduction in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to dismissal and an increase in unemployment.
The Russian business cannot raise salaries, says Vladimir Pantyushin, chief economist of Barclays Capital for Russia and the CIS.
Unemployment near historical lows, competition for workers is high.
In order to lure employees from the outside or to keep the current ones, employers have to raise salaries.
The consumption in Russia is also under the very rapid growth of demand for credit.
According to Mr. Graf, due to the extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of credit does not have a multiplicative effect on the economy of the country.
"We saw no benefits for the economy from the growth of consumer lending, the money does not diverge in the economy, but return to the same banks in the form of interest payments," the economist said.
But the problem is different - Goldman Sachs expects a rise in overdue loans.
They are taken mostly by poor people who have nothing to provide in security.
Interest rates on such loans are high.
As a result, they are not returned more often," - said Mr. Graf.
Therefore, the second threat to economic growth in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payment on unsecured loans.
Vasily Solodkov, Director of the HSE Banking Institute, sees signs of an arzying banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, having no access to cheap resources, which state banks have, were forced to raise the population's funds at high interest rates.
In response, the state banks went to the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rates, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If the state banks do not give up the damping, Russia faces a full-fledged banking crisis, says Vasily Solodkov.
In recent weeks, the economist considers the exercible to be a cestorm of the licenses of a number of banks.
"The state banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was not initially designed for a system crisis," the head of the institute warns.
But the growth of consumption will slow down without a crisis of non-payment, according to the investment bank, due to the refusal to index the wages of civil servants and military, laid in the current version of the draft budget.
Partially the blow to consumption will be softened by the freezing of tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a result, a decline in inflation).
But only partially: if the investments do not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this - see the reference), the growth of consumption will still slow down, are confident in Goldman Sachs.
Vladimir Panthyushin of Barclays Capital does not yet see any prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
"The main risk is still the drop in the price of oil," he says.
According to him, the Russian economy will begin to shrink at the cost of oil below $ 90/bbl.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical pattern: inflation declined, and banks began to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting," Clemens Graf said.
The Central Bank's interest policy does not affect market rates, affects only the interbank lending rates.
"For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes," said Clemens Graf.
The money received at the auctions of the Central Bank, banks are not used to lend to the economy, but to manage their liquidity
As soon as the rate decreases, the exchange rate immediately changes, it means that the funds are trying to go on speculation against the ruble.
"Emerit or later, the Central Bank will understand that this strategy does not work," said Mr. Graf, and reminded that the state plans to launch the ruble into "free voyage" by the end of 2015.
But he believes that it will have to do it before or raise the key interest rate of the Central Bank (5.5%).
According to him, the ruble rate is now artificially overpriced by 10%.
I have only one road - to weaken, - concludes the expert.
But if the Central Bank casts a shadow of doubt in the financiers that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it can hit the ruble much stronger.
