FAU: "Air passengers can now use gadgets on planes (but do not call from a mobile phone) "
Passengers will be able to use their electronic devices throughout the flight to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music, but not to speak on mobile phones, according to the long-awaited new guidelines published on Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers should not expect that the changes will occur immediately.
How quickly this change is implemented, will vary depending on the airline, said the administrator of the FAU Michael Werta at a press conference.
Airlines will have to show FAU how their aircraft meet the new guidelines and that they update their teaching aids for the flight crew members and the rules for laying devices to comply with the new guidelines.
FAU said that it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue were among the airlines that have already presented plans.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the expansion of the use of electronic devices very soon, " said the FAU.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the door of the plane closes.
They should not restart them until the plane reaches a height of 10,000 feet and the captain will not give.
Passengers must turn off their devices again when the plane is reduced to land, and do not include them until the plane is on the ground.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference can allow passengers to use these devices during take-off, landing and steering, said FAU.
Most of the new airliners and other aircraft modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at high altitudes is expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Gleiding, president of the Association of Professional Aconductors, welcomed these changes.
"After the new policy is successfully implemented (and we are going to work in close contact with the carrier to achieve this), it will be a win-win option, Glading said.
We are frankly tired of feeling on duty at school when it comes to this question.
But Internet connection for surfing, e-mail sharing, text messages or data download will still be prohibited at a height of less than 10,000 feet, the agency reported.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices into the mode of the aircraft.
Thus, there are still no "Words with friends" - intellectual Internet games, in which actor Alek Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when there was a notorious case: the actor was removed from the plane of American Airlines for refusal to turn off the device at the time when the plane was at the exit of landing.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be placed in the luggage compartment, as they can hurt someone if they fly around the cabin.
Calls from a mobile phone in flight will also be prohibited.
Regulatory powers by telephone calls belong to the Federal Communications Commission, not FAU.
FAU may remove the ban on some electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Council for Transport Safety, a national expert on transport security CBS News, said that cell phones are still considered to be risk.
"The jack phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially create interference for navigation devices, but we know thanks to the FCS that they can create obstacles to cell towers when the plane is in the air," said Rosenker.
The industry advisory committee, created by the FAU to study this issue, recommended last month for the government to allow the wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAU has increased in order to weaken the restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri democrat Senator Claire McCasquill, claim that there are no good reasons for the bans related to security.
Compliance with restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure, as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
FAU began to limit the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of interference for navigation and communication equipment, when passengers began to carry FM radio receivers - high-tech gadgets of the time.
New airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also developed and approved by FAU as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines offer passengers the use of Wi-Fi at the cruise height for several years.
The aircraft modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of liners are adapted for the wider use of electronic devices according to the new guidelines, said Werta.
Today's electronic devices usually emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
Devices for reading e-books, for example, radiate only minimal signals when page flips.
But signals become more powerful when devices download or send data.
Amazon.com was among those seeking restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers.
In 2011, the company's representatives downloaded a whole airliner with their devices for reading e-books Kindle and flew on it to check the presence of problems, but did not find them.
Members of the advisory committee of the FAU expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of devices is any risk.
Douglas Kidd from the National Association of Air Passengers said that he considers the interference from the devices real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee said that there are only individual messages of pilots confirming that devices can create obstacles for aviation systems, and most of these messages are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAU allows pilots to require passengers to disconnect the devices during landings on the devices in limited visibility.
The group of representatives of the tourism industry welcomed these changes, calling them a sane step towards passengers who are now using many technological devices.
"We are pleased that the FAU recognizes that the comfort of passengers is not incompatible with the safety and protection," said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Tourism Association.
