New antinicotine vaccine can deprive the process of smoking pleasure
Scientists have developed an antinicotine vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarettes pleasure.
One dose of vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
Further tests are needed before the trials on people, which will take a few years, but Professor Ronald Crystal from the Medical College of Well Cornell in New York said that the first results are encouraging.
We very much hope that such a strategy of vaccine application can finally help millions of smokers who tried to quit by having tried to try to try out all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine dependence is strong enough to overcome it with the help of these modern means," said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry genetic information for the production of antinicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a stable flow of antibodies.
Antibodies track any molecules of nicotine in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the receipt of nicotine shock by the smoker.
In the tests, vaccinated mice, which were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activities.
And the mice, which did not give the vaccine, were sweetened, and this is a sign that nicotine came to their brains, - the researchers say.
These experiments are described in Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
In order to maintain a high level of antibodies, injections had to be done so often that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into an antibodies factory.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they had a desire to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that it will be used by smokers to quit smoking.
"They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not get pleasure from it because of the nicotine vaccine, and it can help them get rid of this habit," he said.
British scientists said that the results were interesting, but warned that additional research is necessary.
