According to the instructions of the Federal Service for the Protection of the Constitution (BfV), the German internal intelligence service, his task was to photograph the roof of the US representative office building, which is less than 5 km from the European Central Bank and Bundesbank.
German media say that BfV hoped to detect antennas of listening devices, and these actions entailed negotiations between the United States and the German Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Berlin.
James Clapper, director of the US National Intelligence Agency, once again assured in September that the U.S. does not use the possibility of foreign intelligence to steal commercial secrets of foreign companies in the interests of American companies to increase their international competitiveness or increase their profits.
But since Edward Snowden, a contract officer who became the exposer, began to publish his treasury of the secrets of the U.S. intelligence, European governments and company leaders are no longer sure whether it is possible to believe the director.
Reports that the US National Security Agency followed the Brazilian oil company Petrobras and gained access to data stored by U.S. cloud service providers, including Google and Yahoo, raised the paranoia of corporations caused by state surveillance to new heights.
The last drop was the news that Chancellor Angela Merkel's phone had been listened to, perhaps, for about ten years.
If the most influential person in Europe can become a target, then, of course, potential targets are business leaders.
Snowden made obvious intensive cooperation between US intelligence services and companies.
I think it is likely that this data is used with mutual benefit.
"Germany must wake up," says Oliver Gryun, president of the BITMi association, which represents small and medium-sized IT companies in Germany.
German companies are convinced that the U.S. is now almost the same risk as China, in the field of industrial espionage and data theft, according to a study published in July by the consulting agency EY.
In all the documents disclosed by Mr. Snowden, however, there has been no evidence that the United States has transferred commercial secrets to foreign companies to its own companies.
Politicians expressed concern that the EU lacks certain opportunities in the field of information technologies and the Internet, and expressed the opinion that it should try to reduce its dependence on the United States.
Businessmen are skeptical about this.
Someone in the German parliament says that we should create German Google.
I can only close my eyes and slowly open them again...
This is not an option, says Gasso Plattner, president of the German software provider company SAP.
If there is a need for a powerful European IT-industry, it was not worth to let it die more than 20 years ago.
Everything is subsidized in Germany: from coal to cars and farmers.
Everything except the IT industry.
Nevertheless, the coverage and technical development of U.S. espionage agencies, which became known thanks to Snowden's revelations, were shocked by some companies that used to think that China was the biggest risk of surveillance.
A big shift takes place in cloud technologies, where European companies have better realized that the data stored in the United States are in the same jurisdiction and therefore potentially vulnerable.
According to a study conducted by the Cloud Security Alliance trade association, about 10% of its non-American participants refused to use the services of the US cloud provider after the US disclosure program for the intelligent Prism data analysis.
Jim Sneib, one of the executive directors of SAP, said: "We see that consumers are asking a new question that did not arise a year ago, namely: where my data is stored and whether you can guarantee that they will physically remain in this jurisdiction.
Many German leaders claim that the latest reports are just a confirmation of what they already knew: powerful states want to steal their most valuable secrets, and therefore, these data must be protected at any cost.
What is going on is not surprising.
He always happened.
This was the subject of discussion for many years and has not changed significantly in the current polemics," says Kurt Bock, Chief Executive Officer of BASF chemical company.
Americans spy on us at the commercial and industrial level, and we also spy on them because it is part of our national interests - to protect our commercial enterprises.
The leaders of corporations usually do not like to boast of the response measures they have taken, as this can give an advantage to the opponent.
In large companies has long been learned the idea that to take a free USB flash drive at the exhibition or leave a laptop unattended in the hotel room - it is at least careless.
Ulrich Hakenberg, member of Audi's automotive company's board, says that for many years it's a standard practice - collect mobile phones before the board meetings so that they can not be used as listening devices.
The Federal Service for Protection of the Constitution of Germany recommends the heads of companies to consider the use of simple prepaid mobile phones during foreign trips due to vulnerability of smartphones.
Prepaid mobile phones are subsequently discarded.
However, there are fears that small and medium-slee companies remain vulnerable to hacking and surveillance.
In Germany, many such companies are the leaders in the world market in their specific niche.
"Little and medium-sized companies often lack experience, employees and financial resources to effectively protect corporate secrecy from unauthorized access, - warns in the report BfV.
The U.S. warns its own companies about economic espionage from other countries.
The Washington Post states that the U.S. National Intelligence Report in February put France together with Russia and Israel in a number of violators who are engaged in hacking for economic intelligence, after China.
A member of the board of directors of a prestigious German company confirmed that when it comes to economic espionage, the French is the worst.
Bernard Skarsini, former head of the French internal intelligence agency DCRI, said in an interview this month: "Services are well aware that all countries, even when they cooperate in the fight against terrorism, spy on their allies.
