Sony expects lower annual profits
Japanese electronics manufacturer, Sony, completed the past quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, reduced the forecast for profit for the current financial year.
Sony's results for the period from July to September 2013 were more depressing than expected due to the decline in demand for TVs, video cameras and personal computers produced by the Japanese corporation.
Sony's TV business, which in the second quarter brought the company's first operating profit of 5.2 billion yen in the first three years, fell again to 9.3 billion yen of operational loss.
The Japanese consumer electronics market is going through difficult times, especially due to the decrease in demand for TVs.
And while competitors are trying to look for a way out of the difficult situation, Sony continues to focus on the consumer segment.
For example, one of the main rivals of Sony, Panasonic Corporation, has recently shifted focus on industrial components: here the company's sales are growing at a high rate, especially due to automotive systems and environmentally friendly technologies.
As a result, by the end of the fiscal year, which will end in March 2014, Sony expects to receive 179 billion yen of operating profit against the expected 230 billion yen.
At the same time, according to the agency Thomson Reuters, analysts assumed that this figure will be much higher and will be 221 billion yen.
Aiming to get out of the crisis, Sony expands the product line.
In the middle of this month, the start of sales of "smart" hours from the Japanese corporation, endowed with a number of fashionable features that will get rid of the need for 100 times a day to get out of the pocket smartphone.
After Sony lowered its annual profit and revenue forecast, the company's shares lost more than 11% at the opening of Tokyo's torogs in the morning, dropping to 1668 yen per share.
