Rosbalt Agency Deprived Media Status for Slander
On October 31, the Moscow City Court decided to invalidate the license on registration of the Rosbalt agency, - writes "Lenta."
Roskomnadzor insisted on depriving the agency of media status - for systematic and gross violations of the media law.
In the course of the trial an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, in fact refusing to issue the newspaper the right to propose counterarguments.
What is Rosbalt
CJSC Rosbalt Information Agency was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened the second head office in Moscow and a number of regional divisions.
The agency also has representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency's exclusive publications was (and still make up) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the proximity of the publication to the security agencies continued throughout the existence of the agency.
Along with the fact that "Rosbalt" had a vast base of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions said the fact that Natalia Chaplin - the wife of Victor Cherkesov - was at the head of the project.
At the same time, Chaplin's role in the management of Rosbalt is not completely clear: most often it is called "the project manager."
The agency's general director is Larisa Afonina, editor-in-chief is Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt has not appeared in the ratings of the federal media - neither citation nor the audience.
In October, the agency took the 25th place in the attendance rating of Russian media sites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the past five months - notes about the Kremlin's helplessness in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group "King and Joke," pogroms in the capital Biryulev.
Rosbalt's conflict with Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the media law came into force that banned journalists from obscene abuse.
The agency found the banned vocabulary in two videos published on the agency's website ("Jigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot defiled oil towers").
Further sides are described in different ways.
Roskomnadzor, based on the discovered videos, accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the media law and appealed to the court with a request to withdraw the license from the agency.
Rosbalt stated that the agency's claims were inappropriate: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, and secondly, their mother's words were disguised, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed Roskomnadzor's complaints in the world court - and when on October 22, 2013 the Moscow City Court accepted Roskomnadzor's claim, the consideration of these complaints was still continued.
However, the judge made a decision not in favor of Rosbalt on the 25th day of the world: editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code of administrative offenses and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the Moscow City Court hearing - if we give up the idea that the outcome could have been predetermined earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate the certificate of registration of Rosbalt, in fact depriving the agency of the status of media.
It is impossible to say that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The agency was supported by Duma deputies (the statement addressed to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document was submitted on the initiative of the CPRF).
Head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, Chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and Head of the Presidential Human Rights Council Mikhail Fedotov said about the inappropriateness of the publication.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, Roskomnadzor's leadership even provided him with some guarantees that the license will not be revoked.
The Rosbalt trial showed that under whose jurisdiction it is safer to be a media outlet in Russia today is a big question.
