Syria has destroyed chemical weapons equipment
Syria has destroyed all the declared capacity for the production of chemical weapons, recognized the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons.
This first stage of disarmament of Damascus completed the day before the deadline.
Until November 1, Syria was supposed to destroy production and other auxiliary facilities designed to prepare combat poisonous substances for use, BBC reports.
The destruction of the stocks of poisonous substances or their chemical components should be completed by mid-2014.
According to the OPCW representative, currently the poisonous substances are in sealed repositories.
International inspectors went to Syria after more than 1,400 people were killed during a chemical attack on the outskirts of Damascus on August 21 during a chemical attack.
The main task of the inspectors was not to waste time - in order not to allow the Syrian authorities to produce more chemical weapons - and to destroy the infrastructure for mixing chemicals and ammunition equipment.
These production capacities will now be closely monitored to prevent their repairs.
The next veha is the middle of November: by this time the OPCW and the Syrians must agree on a detailed plan to destroy the existing stocks of poisonous substances.
There are many questions here.
Where will they be destroyed?
Who will provide the equipment for this?
All Syrian statements will be carefully checked by the Western intelligence services.
They will willingly advise the inspectors new objects to check if they suspect that Damascus is not completely frank.
The U.S. believes that this shelling was conducted by regular troops.
Syria and Russia insist that this is a work of the Syrian rebels.
The world community demanded from the Syrian leadership - in accordance with the agreement reached through the mediation of Russia - to destroy or disable all the capacities for the production of shells, poisoning gases and liquids and to fill the projectiles with these substances.
Now that this stage has passed, the next step should be the destruction of chemical weapons already available in the Syrian army.
It is assumed that in this arsenal there can be more than 1000 tons of nerve-paralytic poisoning substances, sebum-slab mustard gas and other prohibited chemicals stored in several dozens of different places.
For its destruction, it is necessary that the OPCW and the Syrian authorities begin to agree on the schedule of action - it takes two weeks.
Head of field operations OPCW Jerry Smith said BBC that his inspectors "personally monitored the destruction of equipment."
"They are now not able to continue producing or mixing chemical weapons," he said.
The OPCW statement says that the inspectors visited 21 of 23 objects in Syria and were convinced that the plants for the production of shells and poisonous substances were either destroyed or brought into dissusability.
The remaining two objects are too dangerous to carry out inspection there, the document says, but the equipment was transported and checked by OPCW specialists from there.
According to Smith, the process of destruction of chemical weapons infrastructure was "especially difficult," as it had to work in the conditions of the ongoing conflict.
In early October, the OPCW received the Nobel Peace Prize, however, Smith said that the time to celebrate this with inspectors has not yet been found - they were too busy with work.
