Here are the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the European crisis, the project "Europe" is officially dead.
Throughout the European Union, the parties that oppose the EU or for the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining strength.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic party - the alternative for Germany - founded only this year - appeared from nowhere and received almost five million votes in the September federal elections, thus essentially supplanting the Free Democrats (the analogue of our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been an internal opposition to the plan for the creation of federal Europe.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis has become a turning point.
The saving measures introduced by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shekel imposed on national economies through the preservation of a single currency, led many people to the idea that the project "Europe has gone too far."
The euro crisis is little due to the fact that national governments are working with excessive budget deficits, which was true only for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members at exchange rates advantageous for German exporters, which German politicians want to maintain.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe finds itself in a pre-funable position on production capabilities in comparison with Germany.
The only saving agent is to cut wages and public spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current problems of the budget and currency is a deeper problem of productive abilities in Europe.
As a result of a set of green energy measures introduced by Brussels, the cipher, which means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer, the European industry pays twice as much electricity and four times more for gas than in the United States.
This is paralyzed unfavorable price conditions, as we have already seen in Grainjum.
No wage freezing in the world will stop the crushing victory of the cheap US shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, revolt is ripe, especially in France, once the most ardent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite considered the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on the same level with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of obtaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the ruined economy of France in distress.
The right-wing party against the EU, Marine Le Pen, has just won the decisive additional elections, having dropped the ruling party of socialists to the third place.
"Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote - a timely warning to British laborers that it is impossible to assume that the split among the right will automatically affect the left.
What does Le Pen do with his new-invented popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against a single currency.
If this is very likely the parties against the EU will receive support in these elections, such a bloc will be able to take the dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
Here is my opinion: the growing moods against the EU and against a single currency in Europe will merge together to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become a sort of vague "Europe) nations, which liked General de Gaulle.
Germany and its several economies can save the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I assume that the UK is distanced from this project, hoping to get closer to the United States.
Nevertheless, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific Ocean indicates the likelihood that the UK will remain unattended in the cold of the Atlantic.
In what position does this leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region (in fact) of Small England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, to send Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland will be able to succeed within the framework of a more free European agreement provided that we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in non-Federal Europe nations.
Otherwise, we should consider the possibility of repetition of Norway's experience and preservation of our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party's government in Scotland is, strangely enough, the most successful political movement in Europe, against austerity measures, which received an impressive majority of votes in 2011 due to objections to the reductions of expenditures proposed (and implemented) by the ruler of the Treasury ruler Aleister Darling and the subsequent coalition of the tori and liberal democrats.
