Indeed, the demand in various parts of Southeast Asia is where the amount of household debt is growing, such that ValueMax, where it conducts its transaction, this week became the third pawnshop registered on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
The loan secured jewelry is not just a quick way to get money (S$1300 in the case of Amirthaling), but also almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Usually pawnshops in Singapore accrue an effective annual interest rate of 17 % - just above 15.4 % offered in the United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping center.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require credit checking or salary evidence and can issue loans faster than banks.
Therefore, millions of people in the whole region turn to pawnshops, as families feel pressured due to increased cost of living and rapid growth of debts of households and consumer debts.
After five years of steady growth, which followed the global financial crisis, and cheap loans fueled by free monetary policy in developed economies, low- and middle-income families turn to pawnshops to compensate for the decline in revenues as their economies slowed down.
This week Standard &amp; Poor's, the rating agency, indicated an increase in the family leverage, mainly due to the growth of mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
It stated that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest debt ratio of households to the gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia topped this list with 80% of GDP compared to 60 % in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, data showed a continued decline in exports and weakening consumer demand.
The fact is that with the rise in prices people in the middle and lower part [the towers of income] will look for ways to replenish their incomes where they can, - says Song Seng Wun, economist CIMB, Malaysian bank.
Record high gold prices in the last two years strengthened the rush with which people lay their personal belongings, as they use the opportunity to get money for their family decorations.
In Singapore, about 70% of things, laid in 200 pawnshops of the city-state, are gold products.
People say: "The target for gold looks good, let's put the grandmother's golden chain and get it back next month."
In Thailand, the largest pawnshop operator EasyMoney observed an increase in the number of customers using its branches in recent months, up to 20 %.
The growth in pawnshop business is such that ValueMax, the operator of the branch in Bendemir and 15 other similar in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia, where it has four stores, but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, Executive Director of ValueMax.
The company will finance the expansion using 60 percent of S$66mn raised this week as a result of the placement of shares on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some creditors have caused criticism due to high interest rates, Yeah says that pawnshop not only offers cheaper tariffs than other creditors, it also does not increase the debt directly.
"Clients lay the items they already own, and monetization of personal assets does not increase household debts," she says.
The deposit is gaining more and more public recognition as a means to obtain short-term, secured financing.
And at the same time pawnshops use not only those categories of people who are in a difficult financial situation.
Rich people in Singapore also use the ValueMax divisions, laying gold bullion or Rolex watches that can give up to 60 percent of their purchase value in cash.
We see customers from all strata of society.
"They include wealthy individuals who need to borrow money for a short time for commercial projects or investments, or small businesses that need to overcome temporary monetary difficulties," says Mrs. Yeah.
