Postal: Obama's electoral staff considered Biden's exclusion in favor of Hillary Clinton
According to The New York Times, President Barack Obama's closest advisors secretly considered the possibility of replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton on the 2012 electoral list.
This is the discovery of the most vivid sensation of all the expected book by Mark Galperin and John Hailemann about the 2012 campaign "Becomes doubled: The game has changed 2012."
The Times received a copy of the book to be released and reported on Thursday evening that the next presidential aides had conducted large-scale research in focus groups and public opinion polls at the end of 2011 to assess whether Biden's exclusion could help raise Obama's extinct hopes for re-election.
According to the political observer of The Times Jonathan Martin, the book gives a detailed description of the attempts of high-ranking officials of the electoral staff and the White House, namely the former head of the White House administration Bill Daley, to assess the effect of the appointment of former Secretary of State Clinton as Vice President.
The possible replacement was a secret, carefully guarded at the Chicago electoral headquarters and in the Oval Cabinet.
Only six closest advisors to the President, including Daley, former head of Obama's electoral staff, Jim Messin and former senior advisers of the White House David Axelrod and David Pluff knew that the replacement was being considered.
The book "States are doubled" asserts that Daley was the initiator of an attempt to replace Biden, despite their close personal relations, but eventually gave up this step when their data showed that the addition of Clinton to the electoral list would not improve Obama's chances.
In an interview with Martin Daley confirmed that the administration really considered the possibility of replacing Biden Clinton.
"I actively spoke for the consideration of many things, and it was one of them," said Daley to the newspaper.
You must remember that at that time the president was in a terrible form, so we thought: "Oh God, what should we do?"
Although Daley described the study as a necessary test, Martin told CNN representative Anderson Cooper that the electoral headquarters has invested a lot in examining whether this step will bring dividends to voting.
"Elimbing staffs do not spend such amounts of money on surveys and focus groups, if they do not consider something seriously," Martin said in the AK 360 program.
It is unclear whether Obama knew that his team had studied the possibility of substitution.
Martin told CNN that he had asked Daly if he knew his then boss about a possible re-sup.
Although Daley said he did not think that the president was aware of the possible replacement, the former head of the administration admitted that, perhaps, Obama knew.
Martin added that the "Study is doubled" does not give a clear answer to the question whether the results of political sensing reached Obama's desk.
Cooper asked Martin if he seriously believes that Obama did not know about the study of the possibility of expelling Biden from the electoral list.
"Perhaps," Martin replied.
