Two YMCA employees accused of sexual crimes before being charged against Jonathan Lord, as the Royal Commission became known
Two YMCA NSW employees were accused of sexual crimes against children before the 2011 accusations against a childcare employee in Caringbach Jonathan Lord, the Royal Commission for Sexual Violence reported.
But in the opening statement of the Commission it was said that she had never had a case of sexual violence against children inside her organization.
Chief Executive Officer Philip Hayre was asked about one case when YMCA employee was accused of crimes related to child pornography, and another case when the gym instructor at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted for sexual crimes against children under his supervision in 1991.
Mr. Hayre told Geil Ferness, a lawyer who was assisting the commission, that he knew about the first case, but he did not know about the second.
He admitted that YMCA in the opening speech for the commission also made inaccuracy, claiming that there were external inspections of YMCA, who admitted that YMCA was in the front ranks to ensure the safety of children.
The presented commissions testimonies indicate that YMCA was notified that it received the second from the end of four possible assessments based on the results of the quality audit carried out by the Department of Education and Communities in August this year.
Mr. Hayre, who joined the YMCA when he was 21 years old, admitted that he and the lower leadership had missed the Lord, and also failed to provide a clear understanding of the staff's commitments regarding the reports of child safety violations.
Earlier this year, the Lord was convicted for sexual crimes against 12 boys for two years of his work at YMCA.
He was imprisoned for at least six years.
But Mr. Hayre rejected the assumption that YMCA's corporate ethics prevented employees from reporting violations of the Lord in the field of child safety.
The staff gave evidence that they were observing violations, including the fact that the Lord was alone with the children, personally cared for them, knelt them, said that he loved one of them and allowed them to play their mobile phone.
Daniel Okwell, who was under the guidance of the Lord and asked to teach her the protection of children, because she was concerned about his behavior, testified that she found Jackie Barnat, the child care manager of YMCA's department in Caringbach, who was the leader of the Lord, who was a very frightening and often inaccessible.
The Executive Director said that he did not accept the explanation of the staff that it was embarrassing for them to report the situation to their superior leaders.
Rather, according to him, their friendship with the Lord led them away from the idea of the need to report it.
Mr. Hayre said that he presented to the Council of YMCA of New South Wales his opinion that the lesson for organizing the incident with Jonathan Lord is not referring to the provision of information from the staff, and the advice agreed with him.
Mr. Hayre said that the decision to force employees to sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the appearance of the charges was made by the Director General of YMCA on child care Liam Wytley.
He said that it was intended to prevent the damage of the evidence, but at the same time he was indulged and this decision was poorly implemented.
YMCA New South Wales was not a safe organization for children while working in it by Jonathan Lord in the period of 2009-2011, said the expert on the problems of child planting Professor Stephen Smolboun of the University of Griffith.
He said that there were serious problems in recruitment, selection, instruction, training of personnel and control.
The hearings are postponed until December 20.
