Ben Greenman: The Tenth Anniversary of the New York Comedy Festival: New Yorker
We can safely say that New York is the birthplace of stand-up comedy in America: almost a hundred years ago, the pop artist Frank Fay, who worked at the Palace Theatre at Broadway, began to tell jokes directly to the public in a colloquial manner.
The innovation of Fay over time picked up others, quite recently - the New York comedy festival.
Created and supervised by Caroline Heursh, the founder of the Carolines stand-up club, celebrates this year its tenth anniversary, counting more than sixty shows in small clubs and large theaters.
"Mo more of these headliners started in Carolines, and then achieved more success, reached a level when they are already too famous to perform in the club, "Hursh said.
We created this festival as a way to continue with them work.
This year's event includes performances by Vanda Sykes, Kathy Griffin and Bill Mara, as well as "Stendap for Heroes" - an annual musical and comedy charity concert for military veterans in Madison Square Garden, where there will be among others Bruce Springstin, John Stewart, Roger Waters and Bill Cosby.
With the expansion of the festival, the world of comedy has expanded.
Several comics participating in the festival this year, gained popularity in non-traditional way, for example, thanks to a show on small TV channels like Comedy Central, FX and Spike.
Nick Kroll became famous for his role in the comedy series on a little-known cable TV channel (only scoring "Liga" on FXX on the theme of fantasy-football), and now conducts his own sketch show at Comedy Central.
Jenny Slayt joined the acting composition both in the Saturday evening in a live broadcast, and in the Parks and recreation areas, although it is most known by a series of virus videos "Marseille - a shell in shoes."
Both Kroll and Slait, like other young comedian with original style (sur-realistically pessimistic Anthony Gesselynik, cunning, focused on racial themes Kamau Bell), is the result of a decentralized world of American comedy.
One of the highlights of the festival will be David Steinberg's interview with Larry David.
Steinberg started as a stand-up comic, but then became a successful director on television and in cinema, as well as an informal historian of comedy.
From 2005 to 2007 he was the host of the TV show Land called Down Comedy with David Steinberg.
The meeting will be held in the Town Hall in the center of Manhattan.
"This city is certainly the central element of Larry's work," said Steinberg.
He told me that when he came here, he sometimes walked along some street between two houses and thinks, "Here I stayed without money, maybe I'll live here."
